  <mads:note type="source">Smith's Dictionary of Greek and Roman Biography and Mythology: "Glaucippus, a son of the Athenian orator Hyperides, is said by Plutarch (Vit. x. Orat. p. 848), who 
    calls him a rhetor, to have written orations, one of which, viz. against Phocion, is mentioned by Plutarch himself. (Phoc. 4
    comp. Athen. 13.590 Sid. s. v. Γλαύκιππος Phot. Bibl. Cod. 266. p. 495, ed. Bekker.) Whether he is the same as
    the rhetorician Glaucippus, of whom a fragment is preserved by Seneca (Controv. 4.25), or as the Glaucippus
    who wrote on the Sacra of the Athenians (Macr. 1.13), is uncertain...."</mads:note>
